The Prague Stock Exchange fell to a minus at the end of trading
After the morning's sharp collapse, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses.
Transactions with CEZ shares accounted for almost half of the normal daily trade.
Since the start of Tuesday’s trading, the Prague Stock Exchange has been in a downturn since Monday, when it has fallen nearly six percent.
This time, the stock market is down on Wall Street.
This is how the market reacts to the result of the U.S. House of Representatives vote, which refused to support the plan to stabilize the financial sector there.
The fall of stocks in Asia
The stock market in Asia experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, although the indices eventually wiped out some of the losses over the course of the day.
The Hang Seng Index in Hong Kong declined nearly four percent during trading, but later some of the losses were erased and the decline was reduced to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which tracks the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
The shares on the Sydney stock exchange lost more than five percent, but eventually fell to 4.3 percent.
The stock market in Taiwan fell by 3.6 percent, according to the index.
“The timing of the US bailout is uncertain and will affect financial markets around the world,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines its monetary policy independently, i.e. without dependence on the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, U.S. lawmakers should quickly return to talks and approve a proposal to support the financial system.
Other countries are at risk of being affected as well.
Bloodbath of American Stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected a plan to support the financial system, which was to be spent up to $700 billion (nearly CZK 12 trillion).
The lawmakers ignored President George Bush’s call to support the plan.
According to Bush, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday and major stock indices saw their biggest decline in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell nearly seven percent, and it last saw a decline of a similar magnitude in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but as soon as it turned out that the proposal in the House did not pass, the index found itself in a free fall.
Congress says U.S. government could pump $700 billion into banks
The top U.S. Congressional officials and President George W. Bush’s government agreed on a broader form of financial assistance agreement for the U.S. financial system.
It will be voted on at the beginning of next week.
U.S. lawmakers have made a breakthrough in talks to approve a bailout plan in the form of $700 billion in financial assistance to the U.S. financial system.
However, it has not yet been won.
Congressmen must complete some details of the agreement before they can publish the final form of the law and vote on it.
The plan to support the financial system will be discussed on the floor of the House of Representatives on Monday.
On Sunday, Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Services Committee, told Reuters.
According to sources, the plan could be voted on in the Senate on Wednesday.
According to economists, the announcement that a bailout plan will be approved should be the first significant psychological factor for the recovery of financial markets.
But then there will be "sobriefing" due to the complexity of the mechanisms to help markets achieve even in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made great progress.
"We have resolved our differences of opinion on what the shape of the market stabilization package should look like," Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat, told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could take place on Sunday.
Lawmakers met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Sunday night to give a definitive shape to the government fund.
It should buy back non-sale mortgage assets from financial companies, which draw financial firms into heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
“We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and must also be effective in the market.
We still have a recovery plan to go through, but I think we’re there,” Paulson said.
Signal for Asian Trading
The global financial crisis is severely affecting stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to Nevada Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are trying to reach a definitive agreement in Congress on Sunday.
They want to reassure investors before trading in Asian financial markets, which are the first in a time zone where Congressional decisions could affect Monday trading.
However, it is not yet clear when both chambers of Congress will vote on the bill, nor whether the last-minute talks can be stuck on any problem.
Lawmakers hope it will be approved in the next few days.
The law, however, will undergo a number of changes.
The total amount allocated to the aid scheme shall be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush has demanded.
But Congress can block the release of the remaining amount if it feels that the program is not fulfilling its function, in the wake of another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush praised the progress in the negotiations
The president may veto the decision, but Congress may overrule his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program, which was to acquire finance to buy back bad mortgage securities, whose value has declined because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to repay their mortgages, has been preserved.
“We worked out everything.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday and the Senate on Monday," Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
U.S. President Bush is also pleased with the progress made in the negotiations.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated "the two-party effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Restrictions on gold parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, the negotiator-in-chief, said the legislators agreed on responsibility for the monetary program, protecting taxpayers from losses, closing reliefs, timing of financing the plan.
The new law also aims to limit the so-called golden parachutes for directors of companies participating in the program and establishes a committee to oversee the fund.
It should be run by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on this and we have made great progress towards an agreement that will work and be useful for the market and for all Americans," Paulson said.
The plan also counts on help for homeowners who have problems with repayment.
The government should negotiate new repayments on the mortgages it buys in order to reduce the monthly cost of repayments for debtors and allow them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to Chief Economist Patria Finance David Mark, the proposed plan is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to implement.
“It’s because we don’t know what mechanism and at what price the problem assets will be redeemed.
This will determine how the financial sector and the government will divide the losses," Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be approved now or early next week, according to Mark, is not as important.
“It is much more important for Congress to agree this week that they support this plan and that they will dedicate it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement for approval is of the utmost importance at the moment,” Marek stressed.
Battle on the blade of a knife: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you on how to choose
While almost every mobile can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make a phone call.
It seems clear that it is better to just buy a phone.
Yet there are plenty of reasons for a person to buy a separate player.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the claims of the future owner.
It’s probably hard to get a top-notch expensive turntable at home to listen to the latest Maxim Turbulenc album on it.
On the one hand, such music products on LP records are not based and there is no objective reason for this from a qualitative point of view.
However, if your shelves are full of vinyl with art rock, jazz or blues, you are probably at least dreaming of such a phonograph.
The same goes for music on the go, that is, music compressed, simplified - music in MP3.
There are also price and quality categories.
For someone it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for a player, just as a fan of Pink Floyd will hardly try headphones for twenty crowns from the marketplace.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It also determines the battery life.
Some high-end music players can do much more than just playing music, but what most mobiles don’t even happen to do by chance.
No device today is as versatile as a phone.
In addition to the primary functions, phone and e-mail, he can play music and video, record both, has a better camera, a worse camera, and maybe even can navigate.
And taking into account smartphones and communicators, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
It’s a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no TV can photograph anything.
The universality of mobile also brings disadvantages.
The more features you use on your mobile, the sooner the indicator on the display will send you to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few mobile phones can play music for more than 10 hours, usually much less.
In this sense, the music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
For cheap mobile phones, you can expect that they will not play for longer than a few hours.
If you still call here and there, get another charger to work for sure - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players, you won't have this problem, even the worst ones can withstand at least 9 hours of continuous operation per charge.
Another problem arises when recording music to a mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector, and in addition, not all of them can be directly connected to the computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly to a memory card, but only a few card readers can handle the miniature memory cards used in mobile phones without reduction.
You don’t need any special software for players except for the exceptions (iPod).
Just fill the device with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and players will already create a music library, sorted by the name of the performer, the album name, the genre or, for example, user ratings.
Some devices display only the directory tree structure similar to Windows Explorer, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Players are easier to operate, mobiles are more capable
When selecting a specific device, you are particularly interested in battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of sound output and, of course, control comfort.
If your music is the backdrop and you listen to it every day just for a short time, like in a tram, you just need any mobile phone that plays MP3.
This is something that almost any mobile can do.
You don’t even have to watch what music formats your mobile or player can do.
MP3 can handle everyone and the vast majority of the music that comes to you will be in this format.
It is one of the most widely used and besides it, the vast majority of devices can also handle music in WMA format.
There is less AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods).
Better mobile phones also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
All you need to do is visit the relevant website of the operator (or another provider) and buy a song or album.
This service in itself could already be a good argument for the acquisition of a music cell phone.
Unfortunately, the operator's offer is poor and is usually limited to fast-soaked radio hits.
Prices are not the lowest either.
However, it is generally assumed that the music industry will dominate this way of selling music (whether via GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) in the future.
Most people still carry their cell phones with them.
Whenever you get the urge to listen, you touch your phone in your pocket, while the MP3 player lies forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you also always carry headphones or at least wired handsfree.
If not, you can use an integrated speaker that has almost every mobile, but only a minimum of MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of music phones will be for many price.
The cheapest cost is usually less than $3,000.
For three and four thousand crowns you will get a very decent walkman.
Most of the time, however, you will be limited by the absence of an output to ordinary headphones.
The best and technically the most equipped phones even with a 3.5 mm hole for ordinary headphones cost up to fifteen thousand.
The advantage of the players is, among other things, easy operation.
The simplest - not necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - players can be controlled by everyone.
The minimum of features, the similarity of controls with a previously common cassette player or, for example, a gramophone is obvious.
There is no danger of a collision in the form of an accidentally turned on mobile Internet and then a huge account for data transmission.
What kind of device to touch
Even the cheapest phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of the relevant card you will fit into two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
For basic models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are supported.
Only the most expensive ones can handle 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, touch Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you do not need to spend more than 1,100 kronor.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, go for specialized mobile phones - walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokias and Samsungs).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3 and the comfort of the operator is thus closer to a separate MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose walkman phones have the same user interface as standalone MP3 players.
The same service and in the same price category up to four thousand kroner, but with greater memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours), will take you MP3 players from the above-mentioned brands.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Possibly.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite advanced and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Still, we are missing something here - a virtual operator that would make the classic ones cheaper.
Maybe he won't be long.
We have written many times on Mobil.cz about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
In fact, it was also confirmed by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which noted that the price of SMS is higher with us than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, there may be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are holding so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to get into the fight.
Maybe it sounds paradoxical, but we have three mobile networks and penetration over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, are keen on the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, Chairman of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>) Council, also often reminds them of this, who has expressed several times in the past that there is no room for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic operator with its own network does not seem to have much chance (by the way, it would probably be hard to find frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought a significant price reduction, to which classical operators had to respond.
However, even before the introduction of a stitch like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, similar voices were heard in the UK as in our country.
However, it turned out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
We don’t have to go too far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator has managed to attract more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
The financial group Penta, which owns U:fona in the Czech Republic, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order for them to work efficiently, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They do not entail relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators usually profile themselves as low-cost operators – they offer cheap calls and SMS, but this is often balanced by a narrower range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as cheap as its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, a bet on an undefeated target group can also be a pretty good move.
The company is specifically focused on men.
"Administrative guys choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is hard to say if a similar concept as in Poland could catch up with us.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD>, spokesman for Vodafone, said: “The Czech market is relatively small for the segmental approach on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offerings.”
In the Czech Republic without a chance, say mobile operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not seem very promising.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region," said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, a spokeswoman for Penta Financial Group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything so that no potential competitor arises.
The interest in launching a virtual mobile operator has not been hidden for a long time by the GTS Novera group, which would like to take the next step to become a real competitor of O2 Telefónica in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in being able to offer our customers not only fixed, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already managed to make progress in the negotiations," says group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe it's flashing for better times.
From unofficial information, it seems that we should wait for the first virtual operator perhaps by the end of the year.
For now, however, its emergence is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not think that there is room on the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, no entity has addressed us with a comprehensive and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>en from the O2 Telephony Press Department said in a statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová said: “We have not seen any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to build further.”
He added: “A virtual operator will hardly appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this point, we would already have to have a concrete agreement on the table in order to be able to think about it in this short term."
Vodafone refuses its attention rather to meet the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says: "By working with potential virtual operators, we are open, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider to be the most profitable from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for high-speed mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities - with one-handed operators
The process of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to a fall in prices and thus to a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor?
The fact that when the operators are about something, they are able to pull a rope, is also evidenced by the pulling around the creation of the U:phone.
Probably the biggest pressure towards CTU went at the time of the creation of the U:fon from T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> website.
Now, however, U:fon serves as an argument for not admitting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová said: “The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been further strengthened by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on him and, above all, on his services."
Due to this approach of mobile operators, however, the Czech regulatory authorities are completely uninterested.
It is not just about the position of the CTU, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the United Kingdom and other developed countries - does not have the power to interfere with competition.
They belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
But he took his typical stance on the whole issue.
“The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential candidates was probably not interesting enough for classical operators," said Kristián Chalupa from the Department of Foreign Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS in response to our question.
It is not surprising that such a statement was made by the representatives of the operators.
From an authority to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses their position on the market, this is more than respected.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "At a foreign country where virtual operators are commonly active, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to the reduction of prices for mobile phone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the fall in prices are clearly not in the interests of the EHS.
In fact, shocking to the whole case is the touching convergence of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is offered entirely on its own.
Just like the exact same price of gasoline at gas stations, it is certainly just a piece of chance and a fierce competition.
"The Authority has not found any evidence of anti-competitive conduct in this matter and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore does not have a correspondingly increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market for virtual operators are likely to be available to the telecommunications regulator as well," Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of a dominant position in the market is one of many points of dispute.
There is, of course, an analysis of the relevant markets carried out by the CFU, according to which telecommunications are the sole market from the point of view of competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the creation of a virtual operator always requires the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator - quite logically - has a monopoly on its network.
Therefore, in a certain segment, it must necessarily be dominant.
However, even if we do not accept this argument, it should be at least a warning to <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that the three mobile operators are acting in a similar way.
However, the complaints of a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles when dealing with all operators.
Responsibility-building at CTU is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications, with which <0xC3><0x9A>OHS gives a hand away from the whole matter.
We’ve met him on several similar occasions.
Unfortunately, until the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, the extension of the powers of the CTBT to the field of competition in telecommunications failed to enforce, although a number of experts have promised to improve the situation.
This must be known more than well by the representatives of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
That's what happens when no one's looking
However, the operation of some pseudo-virtual operators remains unnoticed, of which there are several in Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their own price lists of mobile phone services, but they are only partially public.
This is usually done by a multi-level marketing company.
Own mobile phone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The prices of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts towards the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders large quantities of SIM cards.
As a significant customer, you will then receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the trading conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If there were cases you are talking about, it could be a breach of the terms of the contract that we would deal with and could lead to the termination of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrová said.
However, it is quite unlikely that such activity would not affect the responsible people from mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies, they can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators is preventing such a procedure.
In fact, they have considerable profits from the activities of these companies and, unlike real virtual operators, they do not threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out possible problems: “The law allows for similar speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers uses the services of these companies.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card on their phone is not kept in their name, so they cannot dispose of it fully as regular customers of mobile operators."
This is what should be at least odd.
In addition, another question is being opened for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators are closing their eyes to a similar procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the EPA has relatively strong powers to detect a similar activity and, if it does not wish to do so, may not be satisfied with an explanation by operators that they have no idea of such a thing and their trading conditions prohibit it.
When we won't be the most expensive
As has already been mentioned several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a noticeable drop in prices for services.
In practically all countries where virtual operators originated, classical operators tried to more or less prevent their emergence.
The arguments used by them were practically identical - too small, or perhaps too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the developed countries, however, it was at this moment that regulators intervened, which defended not the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, the first virtual operator was created and another was loaded onto it.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing the whole case away like hot potatoes.
From our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguity in competences is more than suitable for them in these cases.
But let's not throw the flint into the rye.
If the behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator will appear with us really soon, the Czech mobile market may move again.
If any of the operators has admitted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And maybe we'll stop calling the railroad than the rest of Europe.
