Prague Highway on Wednesday for the first time on a chip
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will be inscribed in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date when the first passengers will enter the metro, tram and buses, who will have an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
At the moment, it can take about one hundred thousand people who own an Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day and 90-day and yearly coupon (this will be valid from January 1, 2009) and at the same time have it uploaded to their chip card in the infocenters and workplaces of the Transport Company in the subway stations Muzeum, M<0xC5><0xAF>stek, Nádra<0xC5><0xBE>í Hole<0xC5><0xA1>ovice, And<0xC4><0x9B>l, Roztyly, Let<0xC5><0x88>any, Kobyly.
Coupons can also be purchased from yesterday via the Internet on the Transport Company’s website www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than 400 customers by the afternoon.
Those who start using the online store can definitely forget the window in the subway stations, where they have had to regularly stand in long queues for paper tickets.
The coupon will be purchased over the Internet and uploaded to the Opencard card in one of the thirteen branches of the City Library.
"At these places, passengers have access to a service desk with trained staff, which will help them with online purchases and also upload the purchased coupon to their card," said project spokesman Martin Opatrn<0xC3><0xBD>.
In addition to the libraries, it will be possible to upload electronic coupons to the Opencard also in self-service vending machines, which are installed in several halls of the metro.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, the ticket markers remind and passengers may have already noticed them in the metro stations of Roztyla, Bud<0xC4><0x9B>jovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are now five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there should be eighty," he added.
Coupon will check the driver's location of the vending machine
The operation of the vending machines that will start to work tomorrow is simple.
Simply insert an Opencard chip card into them and the previously paid coupon will be uploaded to it itself.
Electronic vouchers from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital, but also in its surroundings.
That is, in suburban trains and bus lines with numbers 300 to 499, mainly residents of central Bohemia municipalities travel to the capital.
"In the trains included in the Prague Integrated Transport, the guides are equipped with card readers, with the help of which they can determine the time and band validity of coupons," explained Filip Drápal of the Ropid organization, which compiles the timetables of the Prague public transport.
Suburban buses have card readers built into the driver’s box.
When embarking, it is necessary not only to show the chip card to the driver, but also to attach the Opencard to the designated place on the side of the treasury.
