Even rats have feelings.
When a rat or cockroach runs away from danger, does that mean that they also feel fear?
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux believes that many animals also have feelings.
But how could it be verified that they feel the same when they behave in the same way as we do?
The online journal "Edge" has been publishing contributions of well-known scientists for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE in its series presents selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without you being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it so far, when we can't even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we begin to engage in a different kind and open up questions of perception or general consciousness, we step into the rough terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it will do the same thing as many other animals: it will pretend to be dead, flee or attack.
Humans behave similarly, of which some scientists assume a comparable subjective experience.
I don't believe that, though.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
This is because the circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its share of short-term memory and executive or control functions).
This vast area is much more developed in humans than in other primates, and appears to be completely absent from other creatures.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including knowing who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that a person is different even from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity could be concealed by the linguistic essence of man: because so much of his perception is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, we could exclude the animals.
But even if consciousness did not matter to language, surely language would influence it, so that animal consciousness, however constructed it may be, would probably differ from most states of consciousness of ours.
Therefore, it is difficult to find out what the consciousness looks like in other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, it is not possible to measure or, because of special hardware, to analyze it on the basis of our own experience, its examination puts us before great problems.
Most of my conclusions relate to the content of conscious experience, but besides that there is another aspect of consciousness that should be scientifically more accessible.
It would be possible to study the processes in the consciousness of animals regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in studies of short-term memory in primates, especially on the example of visualization.
But this approach, which was approached by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, focuses on neural correlates of consciousness rather than causal mechanisms: both may be identical, but perhaps they are not.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the non-frontal cortex for the realization of visualization.
What does it mean for feelings?
I deduce them from the fact that an emotional system, such as the fear system, is activated in the brain conscious of its own activity.
So what we call “fear” is the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as bodily reactions) utilizes operational memory.
Seen from this angle, the feelings are closely linked to those areas of the cortex that are characterized by primates, and especially people.
In connection with linguistic nature, there is a subtle gradation of perception, because with the help of words and grammar we can distinguish and categorize states, so that we can attribute them to others next to ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio believes that feelings arise from more primitive activities in the areas of the cortex and brain stem devoted to physical sensations, similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
