In this edition of Focused on Education, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi will discuss candidates’ positions on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, an academic from California and director of education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is the co-author of the book “Worst than You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs to Choose Schools.”
Effectively addressing Hispanic voters is a daunting matter.
Barack Obama’s educational agenda only proves this.
Obama’s campaign notes that “African-American and Hispanic students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students,” which is true.
In order to combat such performance gaps, Obama’s educational agenda advocates especially, among other things, “transitional bilingual education” for those who are just learning English.
The question for Barack Obama, however, remains whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes the use of languages other than English in the classroom, is no stronger than his interest in reducing performance gaps.
Consider, for example, Sixth Street Prep, a charter primary school in the eastern Los Angeles district.
Students of this school are, in the vast majority of cases, Hispanics from low-income families.
More than a third of students, many of whom have only recently arrived, are still learning English.
Nevertheless, in the state tests in mathematics in 2008, the highest level of incredible one hundred percent of fourth graders.
Almost equally amazing ninety-three percent of fourth graders reached the highest level in the state tests of English language and literature.
This incredible success has been achieved by a different method than that preferred by Obama.
Sixth Street emphasizes control and practice, constant assessment of abilities, and unprecedented access.
Furthermore, and this should be noted by Obama, according to Linda Mikels, director of Sixth Street, the school’s pedagogical approach to those who are just learning English is “complete immersion.”
Immersion in English emphasizes the almost privileged use of English in teaching.
Ms. Mikels, who is against bilingual education, said to me: "We had a tremendous success with one brand new student from Mexico - after twelve months you would go into class and not know what it is."
"It works," she said, "it works for us."
Would Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as a role model for what other schools with large shares of Hispanic and English learners should look like?
The results achieved by the school should be self-evident in answering this question, but the educational agenda of its own party (the National Educational Association is a longstanding proponent of bilingual education) and its own consistent support for bilingual education are blurred.
While Obama agrees that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the matter when he stated that people should stop worrying about “English only” laws.
Instead, “you should make sure your children speak Spanish,” he said.
If Obama really wants to erase performance gaps, he should think carefully about educational patterns that work, rather than ridicule and trivialize them.
Oil falls sharply due to renewed economic worries
Oil prices fell sharply on Monday because of fears that even a U.S. plan to save financial markets would not have to revive the economy.
The price of futures oil trades fell in the morning trading on the New York Commodity Exchange by up to 7 percent to $99.80 per barrel.
Since last Monday, prices have fallen by more than twenty dollars a barrel.
In the past two weeks, commodity markets have been shaken by financial turmoil on Wall Street as well as a pair of strong hurricanes in the Gulf of Mexico.
After peaking at $145.29 a barrel in July, prices dropped to almost $90 a barrel earlier this month, jumping to a surge of huge financial market uncertainties.
Anxiety gripped investors again on Monday, even after the Congressional Presidency announced that it had reached an agreement over the weekend on the biggest bailout plan in history.
This report has been overshadowed by fresh concerns that the financial crisis is far from over.
In the latest episode of the advancing decomposition, the government announced that Citigroup would buy the banking division of Wachovia Corporation.
Meanwhile, the Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments partially nationalized the European financial conglomerate Fortis.
Analysts at Barclays Capital said the furious weekend talks that led to the plan to save the economy "are showing themselves unable to revive the market mood."
As the economic situation worsens, demand for commodities, including oil, is expected to decline.
"The outlook for global stock markets, interest rates and foreign exchange rates has severely weakened," Deutsche Bank analysts wrote in a report to investors.
"We believe that commodities will not be able to escape the disease.
From a commodity perspective, our biggest concern is the extent to which the American virus will spread to the whole world and especially to China.”
Analysts have narrowed their expectations for next year as oil consumption has fallen due to slower economic growth, and have cut their 2009 gasoline price forecasts by about 20%.
