Pride and Barriers to the Lives of Blacks in a Separate City
Hidden amongst the sprawling amusement parks of greater Orlando, a few miles away from everything shiny, noisy and revolving, lies a quiet city where the pride and hardship of African-American life comes to life.
Eatonville, the first completely black city that was incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "a city of five lakes, three croquet courts, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, three hundred good swimmers."
It is now a pilgrimage place.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Eatonville festival Zora! to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains aside, even though she made it a tourist stop by including it in the Florida tourist guide created by the Federal Writers project from the time of the economic crisis.
It’s still as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and didn’t share their real feelings with a white man who “knows so little about us that he doesn’t even know what he’s missing.”
Even today, in a year when the black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open debate on races, many people here remain cautious of foreign views.
“We pay close attention to how our story is told,” says 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the oldest parish in the city.
"It must be right."
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It is both a historical model of black rise and a community of nearly 2,400 people, where the poverty rate is double the national average.
It is a center of literature, but also an oak-shaded example of southern rural black culture – sometimes despised, sometimes praised – that emerged from American slavery.
It is not surprising that the locals are both proud and protective.
And the worries about Eatonville really only started with the Dawn, which is the only way the Hurstons are called here.
She introduced her hometown to the world through heartfelt books full of accents such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
The five paragraphs of the Florida tourist guide transformed the city a bit into Highway 17, which leads through the often overlooked downtown of Florida, into a stage of black history and human drama.
With a big drum in life and literature, Hurston introduced readers to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"On the left side of the road," she wrote, "is a white-brown decorated modern national school with well-maintained courts and playgrounds that Howard Miller always cares about, even though he can't read or write much."
She also mentioned Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and anything that fits in an hour-long hotel."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, remarriage and sex.
This was obviously not the typical Fodor's publishing house.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
"Zora said it the way it was," says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson's girls, who made Hurston immortal by quoting men who sang dirty songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it," she added.
Hurston is still remembered here as a chip malfunctioner who often returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Seventy-seven-year-old Augustus Franklin remembers that most of the time when she arrived in the city, she arrived without warning in the huge Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in the city, which is still proud of its dignified clothing.
Most of the inhabitants were fascinated, Franklin said, but many grumbled.
"The people of Dawn have always loved to see," Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging on a chair on the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were taken out of print.
It seemed that Eatonville had forgotten about her along with the rest of the world.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked tomb in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
There were no major mourning ceremonies or large public readings in Eatonville.
“I don’t think they understood its significance to the world or its legacy at all,” said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston’s 2003 biography Wrapped in Rainbows.
The change came in the 80s of the 20th century.
Representatives of Orange County wanted to extend the city's five-lane highway instead of Kennedy Boulevard, which is a local two-lane main road.
The departure of Orlando has already pushed the interstate highway No. 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still coming from a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, along with other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the fifties of the 20th century, the struggle to mix races brought hatred to the threshold of the community.
"At that time, a bunch of white boys, they came in and threw oranges and stuff at the people who were sitting on the sidelines," Franklin said.
“In fact, there was a woman who was killed.
They threw melons out of the car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston challenged the Supreme Court’s demand for forced integration and declared his ruling in the Brown v. Chamber of Education case to be “offensive to my race rather than commendable.”
Residents now claim that the desegregation of schools, although positive in some areas, has reduced cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of the local youth.
“Black kids were used to hugging — I remember that — you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening,” said N.Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
It took until the teachers and pupils came from the same place, she added.
"You're not embracing your white teacher because your white teacher -- I mean, there's a cultural barrier," said Miss Nathiri.
Civil rights, however, helped to create space for many more Zora Neale Hurston - black writers, actors and artists who like her have risen above prejudices with reckless self-confidence and quotes like "How can anyone deny the pleasure of my presence!
I don't understand that."
In 1975, Alice Walker traveled to Hurston's unmarked grave and began to fight to restore her reputation.
Five years later, the acclaimed biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway, who reintroduced her to the American canon, came to the shelves in bookshops.
The project with the highway arrived just as the most famous daughter of Eatonville again found the lights of the ramp.
The former Hurston neighbors now considered her a saviour.
To show what could happen to its highway to destroy, the community began planning the Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived for the inaugural event two years later, and every January many return to celebrate.
After a few years, the state withdrew from the highway proposal.
"These five streams of the highway have been resurrected, you would say, a direct burst, a real civic pride," Nathiri said.
Boyd put it more simply, "The dawn saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project helped to change the image of the city.
Outsiders such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began attending the local church in 1993, began to appear in greater numbers, and residents began to rethink the past.
Eatonville joined the National Historical Register in 1998.
The new one-storey library (named after Hurston, of course) was opened in 2006 on the re-asphalted and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando can sometimes seem like a dead end in summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded with only 27 black families in the 1980s.
(It's 90 percent black today.)
With strangers coming in search of the story and meaning of Eatonville, it is still often treated with caution.
Permission for most interviews is required in advance and certain things - such as murals in the oldest Eatonville church, painted by whites and depicting blacks in the fields - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Jones, a courageous, self-assured teacher who likes red satiety, are still afraid that their isolated community will not be properly understood.
And as the Hurston Festival grew, so did the domestic pride.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, with problems and so on, but not better, not worse, and as proud, creative, hardworking, foolish, and diverse as other American races and ethnicities.
From the voice of Franklin's nephew, eighteen-year-old Edwin Harvey, a sincere love for the village echoes as he plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the local government or the police, which he says would use some help.
And even younger ones, such as the 11-year-old twins from Winter Park Alondra and Alexia Kenonova, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, when they're just passing by, think, 'Hmm, this town is nothing against the others,'" said Alondra Kenon recently on Sunday after church.
"But if you really stop and look at history for a moment, it's a very nice city."
