"To capture the real character, I photograph the master off-scene." Günther Bauer - photographer
No heels, no bells, no costumes.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, disconnected from the focus on interpretation - only in this way do I achieve a relaxed expression of man or woman.
On the one hand, an artist.
Secondly, a man.
Inseparable, not to mention privacy, in those moments far from the audience - then you can see a familiar gesture, the depth of a glimpsed gaze or a passionate gesture of hands that are carefree, because they are not going to get on stage.
In "Flamenco-people", German Günther Bauer alternates the theatricality of performances with singers, dancers and guitarists with the lesser-known face of the masters.
With this intention, the photographer compiles a unique iconography of flamenco from different backgrounds.
The exhibition, which runs as part of the Mes de la Fotografía Flamenca (Mes de la Fotografía Flamenca) program, "reflects the ever-growing international importance of flamenco," the author says, explaining that "Flamenco-people" "can be any people, but when you look at the photos, you find that it is not typical.
These people portrayed "on the street" are artists capable of bringing passion, sadness, joy to the stage... and completely captivating the audience.
To capture the personality of these artists, it is not necessary to photograph on stage.
He carries his personality and character inside.
I was interested in creating a relaxed atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of the giants of flamenco.
Enchanted by the "Cante de las Minas" festival, Bauer embarked on a long journey in 1997 to portray flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers on a board camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, resemble classical photography.
The use of different stylistic means is contrary to the classical basis of the image and gives it a contemporary spirit, which is an idea that, according to Bauer himself, also reflects flamenco: "Music with very traditional roots, which, however, does not cease to surprise and evolve."
What strikes the viewers is not the effect of the dance, singing or play itself, but the personality and character of the artist.
The search for the moment when we meet with the most essential, with that spirit that manifests itself in the way of perception, being and experiencing, that has been and is the constant of the work presented during these days in the gallery of El Fotómata.
This selection of nearly seventy photographed artists is shaped by famous flamenco figures such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales or Vicente Amigo.
The project has become an anthology of flamenco and will soon have a book edition containing portraits.
Two years ago, Bauer’s passion for portraiture led him to repeat the idea on the “Portraits of Sports Veterans” (“SportARTproject”).
Although their concept is different from "Flamenco-people", the photographer admits that "photographing people, recognizing them and being able for a moment, whether long or short, to enter their lives - that's my passion.
I think portraiture is the most difficult genre in photography.
A person meets or confronts people, personalities he sometimes doesn’t even know, or gives him only a few minutes to shoot.
Despite such circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to realize my ideas.”
The collection of portraits of the contemporary flamenco called "Flamenco-people" is exhibited in the El Fotómata Gallery on the 20th Street, parallel to the Alameda de Hércules, and can be visited until 16 October.
