Conversation - Blood that is sure again
Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was rightly delighted, as Héma-Québec has become one of the most reliable and effective blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he regained public confidence, which was seriously shaken after the blood-contaminated scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is generally known, the state blood reserve managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Board was contaminated with the Immune Deficiency Virus (HIV) and Hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and the lack of public awareness, the Canadian government launched a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at explaining the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and making recommendations not to repeat such a calamity.
While Judge Krever delayed reporting, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this was the role of the Gélinea Committee.
Following the Gélineau and Krever report, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Québec, which was to manage Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society for the Supply of All Provinces and Both Territories.
“When Héma-Québec began its activities in 1998, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the Québec blood system,” recalls Dr. Décary.
"The situation was depressing.
Through constant efforts to improve the safety of blood products and constant work in this area over the next years, we have regained public confidence," he says, proudly adding that at the beginning of 2008 almost 94 percent of the Quebec population already had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is something very fragile".
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
“At that time, we saw many cases of human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new variant of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease,” says a woman who has led the company since its founding in 1998.
"And we didn't know if this disease could spread with blood.
We have therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau report, according to which in the event that we do not know and when the spread of a serious disease is at stake, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by the degeneration of the brain inevitably leading to death, the measures to exclude them.
In April 1999, we therefore rejected blood from people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proved that this disease is transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that it made sense to stick to the precautionary principle.”
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV emerged on the market: nucleic acid (NAT) tests, which allow the donor blood to detect the presence of the virus itself, rather than the presence of the antibodies on which the tests used before were based.
NAT tests have made it possible to shorten the deaf period that occurs between the moment the patient is infected and the moment when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our technicians, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period to less than a week.
We have significantly reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without knowing it and without being able to figure it out.
These improvements allowed to significantly reduce the risk of acquiring AIDS through blood transfusions.
One in 12 million people are at risk of getting blood contaminated with HIV today.
In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone gets HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products annually, it will take 24 years for the first case of HIV transmission through the blood product to appear.
I believe that we can get or prescribe blood transfusions that are necessary to heal today in complete peace of mind,” says Héma-Québec’s head of management.
“The challenge for us for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what kind of disease can occur in the system.
Just last year, the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted to the bloodstream by the stab of insects.
We need to be constantly careful," continues Dr. Décary, stressing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also count on a sufficient supply.
“The needs are growing as the population ages.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for the network of blood donors, which on average consists of only 3% of Quebecers eligible for donation.
Every healthy person is at least 18 years old, according to the eligibility criteria, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
14% of people donating blood are not accepted on average because they are carriers of AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have visited a country where mud colds are treated, they are excluded for one year.
"With this 3%, we can maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
Members of the donor network, however, need to be supplemented in proportion to how old they are and can no longer donate blood.
However, it is difficult to persuade people to donate blood, especially to sustain and encourage them to become regular donors.
“Life is so unfettered today that we rarely find an hour to donate blood,” said Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public bank of umbilical cord blood in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, which was previously considered biomedical waste, flows blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousand cord blood sample into the bank and we expect to collect over a thousand per year.
We should start offering them for transplants early next year,” says Dr. Decary, who describes the cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they don't have access to it," because Héma-Québec doesn't have enough resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
