Opinions - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Discourse
In the September 17 issue, Le Devoir printed a letter from Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwellian logic, he confirms that the world's largest gold producer has launched a prosecution of three authors and a poor little publisher for insulting the honor in order to spark a "transparent public debate" and demands six million from them.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge truthfulness, especially in the case of prosecution for insult to honor, but the law.
It's no surprise that Garver completely misses this crucial distinction.
Or is it the best way for Barrick Gold to lead a public debate, to bring to nothing anyone who dares to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of the book Noir Canada (Black Canada) will be forced to spend respectable sums to be prepared to defend themselves and fight in a very uneven battle with an army of lawyers supported by the almost miserable pockets of a mining company.
The tactics in these uneven fights, by the way, often consist in destroying the defendants in order to enforce conciliation proceedings that will shut the mouths of the counterparty and, moreover, frighten anyone who dares to devote himself to this matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it had to present its view of the whole thing to public opinion.
Contrary to what is happening in a few countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada, the debate normally consists in the exchange of ideas, not in the wounds of the scab.
The mining companies therefore had no choice but to open their books, their documentation, and create a real debate through newspapers, media, publications, and the funding of independent scientific teams that could bring the whole thing to light.
Barrick Gold, however, does not seem to have confidence in public opinion, and shyly rejects petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand a "public debate" and at the same time despise the views of the same public?
In the Vice-Presidential world, this word seems to mean only high-paid lawyers, not all Canadians; that is a rather narrow concept.
In a democracy, they also have the right to speak for themselves.
Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada does so primarily because it rejects the brutal ways of mining society.
The public is ready to hear Barrick and re-evaluate the case, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not within what many perceive as a prosecution in which the defendant should be mouth-closed (as part of their prosecution of the "public debate").
Forget Garver’s surreal speech, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the university’s freedom to research and seek the truth that is essential to any democratic society.
Overall, it denies the right to cite credible sources and to debate the facts and interpretations that constitute the very basis of intellectual activity.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and discuss topics that the rich companies of this world do not like without facing repeated persecution, who else will be able to do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could create it if it followed the scientific norms used by the authors of Noir Canada.
He has the right to an answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
The exaggerated Barrick Gold lawsuit clearly shows that, despite what it claims, it does not have the slightest desire to conduct a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the university world, as well as for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to introduce measures to limit this kind of unjustified prosecution.
Wall Street Rescue Operations - Democrats and Republicans Understand
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
A new version of the plan, using $700 billion to curb the financial crisis that has been sweeping Wall Street for months, still needs to be approved by both chambers of Congress.
In particular, it envisages: better control of its application by elected representatives, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of public money stored, new measures to seize the number of houses seized for non-payment, and also the right to monitor the amount of salaries paid to executives rescued by companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi and Representative of the Republicans at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced this good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, after ending a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress and reached an agreement that will be effective in the markets," Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson said in a statement.
"Everything was done to keep the real economy and ordinary Americans safe from the crisis that is currently taking place on Wall Street," he said.
“That’s a crucial point: if we don’t do it, the trauma, chaos and disruption to everyday life of Americans will be huge,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
Over the last few hours, the negotiations have gone to maximum speeds out of fear of the effect that a further failure at the disposal of investors would have.
The deadline was set for the opening of markets this morning.
Both U.S. presidential candidates were invited to negotiate later, and both expressed their support for the deal, but did not fail to express their dissatisfaction with the need to resort to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has credited himself with supplementing the agreement with some measures, in particular one aimed at enabling homeowners to preserve their homes, and salary measures for state-sponsored workers rescued by companies.
“When we ask taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibility of some people, there is no reason to congratulate them.
However, these measures are necessary," he explained on television.
His Republican rival John McCain, who was asked by another station if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
“The rough traits I’ve read [show] that this is something that we’ll all have to spend and with which we’ll be able to move on.
Choosing inaction is simply unacceptable,” he said.
The 700-billion-dollar plan aims to buy dubious debts and risky and non-sale assets of U.S. financial institutions for taxpayers’ money.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis triggered by the bursting of the real estate market bubble, which first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprimes), then moved to other, more widespread forms of loans (PCAA) and resulted in the freezing of cash and in the decomposition of banks.
The collapse of the first draft of the agreement from last week is on the conscience of Republican MPs.
Since the Democrats have agreed that for some of the "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty, the government will only be liable, but will not buy them out, there is a belief that the unforeseen situation is doomed.
In an effort to rapproche conflicting views in Congress, a measure was enclosed stipulating that the government would be able to introduce new fees that would help it recover its deposit if it had to bear losses for five years as a result of the program.
The new plan expects a first deposit of 250 billion, to which an additional 100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
A further $350 billion is expected to be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will acquire shares in the rescued companies, which will pay him dividends in case of profit, and which he will be able to re-sell when it is all over.
The federal government will be able to delay the seizure procedures of the real estate related to the loans covered by the plan, as well as set limits on the amount of valuations and compensation paid to executives of affected companies.
The plan’s sponsors would like to submit it to a vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts, it is not yet certain whether their plan will be green.
Yesterday, the votes against this project continued to rise in both the Republican and Democratic camps.
“It’s quite clear that Washington is not listening to you,” said Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee.
“Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But making money from taxpayers is not the solution.”
Democratic Representative Brad Sherman, the moderator of a group of congressmen dubbed the "Committee of Skeptics", presents the whole thing differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred distinguished professors of economics, including three Nobel laureates, wrote to us: We ask Congress not to rush too far and to carefully examine which way to go,” he said.
At the same time, it has been reaffirmed in Europe that this crisis is a global crisis.
At the end of the extraordinary meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>11.2 billion (USD 16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from the purchase of its competitor, which is on the brink of collapse since it lost <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2 billion ($2.9 billion) in state losses due to the non-risk crisis.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the 20 largest banks in Europe and one of the ten largest insurers.
"We will not lose this money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
“In return, we gain the right to vote in the bank and influence.
This is something that people and households can appreciate in these uncertain times.”
On the other side of the Channel so far, the British government seems to have begun the nationalisation of another bank affected by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government was to take over all existing loans from Bradford and Bringley, of which more than 41 billion ($75.5 billion) were loans to buy real estate.
According to its announcement yesterday, the Spanish bank Santander will buy the branches and accounts of the British bank’s clients.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank after Northern Rock, which the British government must nationalise since the start of the financial crisis.
