Psychology of trumpeting: Why do we spend more money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overvalue goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this well-known – and seemingly irrational – behavior have been revealed to researchers in the field of neurology and economics at New York University.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people do not want to lag behind in an auction like eBay, so they prefer to pay too high a price.
Research with the help of an experimental auction tried to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers bet, the other group participated in the play auction, using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method to examine the active areas of the brain of the subjects.
In both games, the participants could win money, but when playing at an auction, an important element of which is to beat the other side, the whole under the cortex, called the striatum, began to function intensively during the loss.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region plays a role in the "self-replacement" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, it is possible to explain the price screwing up by trying to avoid a sudden striatal reaction.
To support their theory, members of the research team from among economists conducted a cross-sectional financial survey.
Under different conditions, three groups were bidding against one partner.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they made bets.
Members of the other group were also promised that if they exited the game victoriously, they would receive an additional $15 for the reward.
The third group received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, the members also lost the money.
The difference between the two groups was, therefore, everywhere that one was emphasized victory and the other loss.
Members of the “against losing” group, however, were willing to go higher than they were in the control and “victory” group, which confirms the neuroscientists’ hypothesis.
“These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
They have so far explained the phenomena observed in the auctions of the joys of winning and avoiding risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped us resolve the contradiction between these two theories so that we have now come to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Approximately half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary, this chronic liver disease is listed as one of the leading causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand of them are treated. The reason for this is that the sick often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a summary of infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, characterized by inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but the causes of the disease and the diseases caused by them differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the origins of the disease, spread in two main ways: hepatitis A and E through the digestive system (for example, infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses of blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
Travellers should in any case be protected by vaccination against virus A and B, there is no type C vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after ingestion of infected food, they are usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal problems, compulsion to vomit.
After that, jaundice, lightening of the stools and darkening of the urine will form on the skin and eye whites. Treatment can last for two to three weeks.
Every year, one million people worldwide die from the more serious type of the disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that, according to estimates, only one in ten infected people is medicated.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, the cause of the disease destroys the liver cells insidiously, and so the first symptoms will appear in many cases in 20-30 years.
Therefore, early prevention, carrying out regular screening, is very important.
In three groups, the disease is much more common than the average: among people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, among drug users and among people with tattoos.
At present, the estimated global number of individuals infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since the disease can prove already routine laboratory tests, a person should contact his or her practitioner if he or she notices any symptoms of unknown origin.
With early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body, thus preventing infectiousness and preventing the formation of cancer.
September 30th is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized worldwide by organizations representing the sick in 2004.
Its aim is to draw attention to the chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, to the causes of its formation and to the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Who believes in God, doesn't it hurt that much?
According to the results of recent research, belief in God acts as a certain analgesic, which may have facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists from Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment, examining how belief in the god of pain affects a person, the British newspaper The Telegraph reported.
As part of a rather bizarre survey, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were subjected to electric shocks, while all watched a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholics were able to rule out much of the pain.
Thanks to a technique that examined the human brain in detail, it was also found that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
Research is the first of a series of studies involving scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university.
Exactly the test was carried out by attaching a sparkling instrument to the left hand of the subject, which emitted electric shocks.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to observe two paintings: Sassoferrat’s Virgin Mary from the 17th century and the Lady with the Border of Leonardo da Vinci, painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the study hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary would evoke a certain state of piety in believers, while they chose da Vinci's painting because it does not differ much from the first and seems to them a soothing impression.
The subjects spent half an hour on an MRI scanner and during this time received in four successive parts 20 electroshocks, while separately watching the image with a religious or general theme.
The Catholics said that when they looked at the Virgin Mary, they felt “safe”, as if they had been “cared for” and “quiet, they were filled with peace”.
When watching a religious-themed picture, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they had Leonard’s work before them.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the research, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any highly impressive image, even in atheists, only to find the right photograph.
“We need to find an image that they will perceive very positively, from the position of mother or father,” the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
“Practicing faith should change, and in many cases it will change our personality,” Wright said.
After such great results, it is only a question of what effect it would have on the pain regulation of believers if they showed them some Madonna from Leonardo or a painter of a similar calibre.
Would a view of the good Virgin Mary mean even better results?
