Intelligent car imitates the flight of a beetle
What would be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collisions, if not imitation of the detectors of obstacles occurring in the world of nature?
In bees, for example.
The initial strategic idea of the surprising project, presented at CEATEC in Japan, was brought to the engineers from Nissan by the beekeepers. It was about how to build a new generation of collision-preventing systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has developed the BR23C biomimetic robotic steering system, a robotic minicar with bee characteristics, with the ultimate goal of helping create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
"During the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is actually very similar to our safety protective packaging," said Kazuhiro Doi, CEO of the brand for technology PR and R&D.
An important role is played by the folded eyes, which allow bees to see in all directions at a viewing angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the composite eye, the engineers resorted to the idea of a laser distance meter.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 meters ahead of BR23C in a 180-degree field of vision, calculates their distance, and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which instantly turns into a collision avoidance operation.
The obstacle is caught during a fraction of a second, then the robotic car begins to mimic the movements of the bee and by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent the collision immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this swinging maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive manner.
“If this were not the case, the robotic car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” said Toshijuki Ando, head of the Robotic Car Mobility and Project Laboratory.
It must respond instinctively and immediately, as this technology fits the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the protective packaging, within which precipitation is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
This process should not take longer than a blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or transversely, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be turned.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees in avoidance, only the possibility of rotation, acceleration and deceleration was applied in the case of a robotic car.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, instinctive, intelligent reaction is important, not the ability to process, much less then to store data.
This mechanism must process and respond only to a few incoming signals per second.
It does not need to store and respond using intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it constantly uses only memory the size of a few kilobytes.
It does not need memory with giga- or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step in the development of technology for immediate avoidance, which Nissan estimates could reach mass-produced cars within a decade.
Another application option may be to connect the unit to the GPS satellite navigation system, which, after avoiding obstacles in the road, would lead the driver to the specified final destination.
