Domestic sales prices in the industry rose by 0.1 per cent in August 2008 compared to the previous month, compared with 12.9 per cent in August 2007, the Central Statistical Office reported.
Export sales prices in the industry were 1.1 per cent higher than in July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 per cent year-on-year.
As a cause of the changes in domestic and export prices in industry, production prices were higher by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month, rising by 3.2 per cent year-on-year.
Domestic sales prices in the industry rose only minimally compared to the previous month, by 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices in manufacturing sectors also rose slightly, by 0.1 per cent, compared to July.
The largest price increase occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear industry (2.8 per cent), mainly due to the monthly price increase in the handbag and saddlery industry by 4.6 per cent and in the footwear industry by 2.5 per cent, respectively.
Higher prices for plastics and chemical raw materials caused a significant monthly increase in prices in the production of chemical materials and products (1.6 percent).
Prices fell in the oil processing sector (1.4 per cent), the production of electrical machinery and appliances (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimum - in the woodworking sector (0.1 per cent).
Prices in the paper industry and publishing and printing activities have not changed.
In other sectors of the manufacturing industry, we measured price increases in the range of 0.2 - 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas and water production and distribution sectors, which play a major role in domestic industry sales, prices rose by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the continued effect of the officially scheduled increase in gas prices since 1 July.
In the twelve-month comparison of domestic sales in individual sectors of the manufacturing industry, prices rose the most in the oil-processing industry (32.4%).
In the metalworking sector, 13.2%, in the production of food products, beverages and tobacco products, which has a decisive weight, it was possible to observe a 11% increase in prices.
Prices fell in the textiles and textile products sectors (2.5 per cent) and in the production of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In other sectors of the manufacturing industry, the rate of price growth ranged between 0.6 and 9.1 per cent.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing industry rose by 10.2 percent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas and water production and distribution sectors surpassed previous year’s prices by 18.7 percent.
In terms of segmentation by sector, domestic sales showed the highest monthly price increase (0.7%) in August in the sectors involved in the production of tangible assets.
In the sectors producing consumer goods, prices rose by 0.3 per cent, in the energy-processing and further-processing sectors, prices did not change compared to the previous month.
The largest price increase compared to the same month of the previous year was observed in August 2008 in the energy processing and further processing sectors (16.8 per cent).
In the sectors producing consumer goods, we measured a price increase of 6.8 per cent, while in the case of tangible assets, a price drop of 1.4 per cent.
Export sales prices of industrial products measured in forints increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, falling by 3.9 per cent in the 12-month comparison.
