Occupational accidents, Napolitano: "Resolute prevention"
Every day, 2,500 work accidents occur in Italy, three people die and twenty-seven remain permanently disabled.
Inail values confirm that for 2007 we have about 1,200 deaths as a result of work accidents.
These values testify to the severity of the phenomenon, which remains one of the main causes of death and causes nearly twice as many deaths as murders.
To rekindle the attention of institutions, social and media about this dramatic problem, today, in all Italian regions, Anmil celebrates the 58th National Day of Work Accident Victims set for the second Sunday in October.
"The alarming data circulated by Anmil and the same tragic reports these days confirm the importance of the issue of occupational safety," President Giorgio Napolitano said in a report sent to President Anmil, Pietro Mercandelli, the National Association for the Deaf and Disabled by Work.
The Head of State expresses his lively admiration for the continuous joint effort for safety at work, for the protection of injured workers, for the assistance to the families of the victims and for the participation of public opinion.
“Naturally, there has been an uproar of ‘enough’, sincerely shared in the face of tragedies that, by their magnitude, provoke unrest in the media and participation of public opinion, but everyday reality again offers us dramatic cases, even repeating itself in its dynamics.”
Napolitano does not hide that "there is undoubtedly a resource problem: it is crucial to invest in training and awareness.
Of particular importance are the numerous initiatives promoted in the field of education, in order to give young people facing the world of work a clearer awareness.
It is necessary to draw attention to this phenomenon, not to give up because of its troubling social severity, to apply and improve legislative norms.
Chamber President Gianfranco Fini, for his part, stressed "how the phenomenon of death as a result of an accident at work creates an absolutely critical social state, how it offends the conscience of each of us and forces all institutions to make convincing efforts towards the necessary end of this state."
"As for the work accident data, they seem to be showing some positive turnaround, but this does not deny that the number of deaths as a result of work accidents is as alarming as it is," President Anmilu Pietro Mercandelli said.
“We don’t want this ‘slowdown’ to lead to less attention, because it’s the moment the attention stops that the tragedy erupts.
"We believe that there is still too little to be done in general to stop the problem of injuries and there are many activities that can affect this problem.
In our opinion, it is necessary to increase controls and inspections, but also to intervene more strongly in the training of workers, right from school age.
"There is still a need for further efforts - he added - in terms of communication and participation of public opinion.
But above all, there is a need for a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers towards a phenomenon that constitutes an exceptional social phenomenon.
Mercandelli finally stated that it was a progressive degeneration of the level of compensation rights envisaged for the victims of work and the "removal of supportive care" that the system has been getting into in recent years.
“The goal is to give back to the worker the guarantee of insurance, because the fate of those who hurt themselves must not depend on spontaneity or gifting from time to time by the legislator.”
MP3 Players Accused of Exposing Hearing Risk
Listening to loud music for a long time and using portable music devices like Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing loss.
According to the European Commission’s announcement published today, which quotes the opinion of the Scientific Committee on Health Risks that have emerged recently and have been identified (Csserri) EU in an official report enlarged in Brussels.
“From this scientific view, it follows that 5-10% of those who listen to music using portable musical instruments for at least five years, more than an hour a day a week and keep the instrument at a high volume, are at risk of permanent hearing loss.”
“I am concerned that so many young people, who often use portable musical instruments and mobile phones at high acoustic levels, may unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable way,” Kuneva said.
"Scientific findings - the leader continues - pose a clear risk and need to be responded quickly.
Most importantly, we need to encourage consumers and make this information public.
We need to continue to re-examine existing control systems in the light of this scientific finding, so that they become fully effective and keep up with the new technology.”
Brussels has asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine this problem in view of the high use of portable musical instruments and the growing number of young people exposed to the noise of this origin.
"Scientists - concluded the EU executive - confirm that there is a need to worry, and now the European Commission, together with other members and parties who have raised the problem, will examine what measures could possibly be put in place to better protect children and young people from exposure to noise."
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical instruments to 100 dB, but there are growing concerns about hearing damage that may be caused by excessive exposure to similar forms of noise.
It is possible to greatly reduce these damages by looking for solutions such as reducing the level and duration of exposure.
In its opinion, the Scientific Committee of the EU states that users of portable musical instruments, if they use loud music (more than 89 decibels) for only five hours a week, will exceed the current limits corresponding to the maximum permitted noise in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for a long time are at risk of permanent hearing loss after five years.
This problem should affect 5-10% of users of such devices and their number can be estimated between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
