A few days ago, the House of Representatives voted against the $700 billion bailout plan presented to the White House: a significant proportion of Americans were more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday’s New York Times, which informs us that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, which is increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, more temperate, conducive to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, which, on the other hand, leads the world from conservative to non-conservative.
The soul that arrogantly manifested itself in the vote that I spoke of at the beginning.
But this just quoted thing is just an example of the changes, the great changes that the current economic earthquake is already showing: not only in the United States, but throughout the West and perhaps not only here.
Both in the United States and in Europe, this crisis seems to act as an accelerator of phenomena that have been in the incubation for a long time, which are solidified in the new climate and finally come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary revival of the market, the double category of the State-power in relation to a certain re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis is indeed a crisis of banking financial institutions, which, of course, have strong ties abroad, but in which the budgets of people and families living in a single country, in a single state, are mainly involved.
At the same time, this has created a political problem for those who run it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people and families, who are, among others, voters.
In short, the crisis seems economically global, but politically almost exclusively national.
Political internationality seems to be substantially out of the question or that it has nothing to add: the European Union has given clear evidence, which is divided as always between different interests and different national strategies, and which cannot decide on a single common political line.
And so everyone is waiting for the intervention of the government of each individual state, the rescue plans, the revival of the market, the new rules and, above all, the allocation of funds: when we get into distress, only the states have the economic resources, the amount of financial resources to be able to try to put everything in order.
And also own the necessary resources and powers to use them: two resources of immense value, under certain circumstances, which perhaps no market and no international organization will ever be able to dispose of to a similar extent.
This new emphasis, which the crisis places on the national-state element, is, after all, in complete harmony with the growing importance that the latest economic progress is trying to attribute to one factor closely related to it: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had entered the realm of the web, increasingly sophisticated technology, immaterial, while we were convinced that global finances were already destined to rule the world, from nothing did we realize that our future would have to go with them.
All things, who would say this, can be transported from one place on earth to another, but in any case they are connected, absolutely, to a bounded space, a territory.
So who becomes their ruler certainly has much more cards in his sleeve than who is not, and who has the bad luck to live in a place without grain, without oil, and without water.
I'm getting to the second novelty, which, however, predicts evil.
Whoever speaks of territory, state, government, inevitably speaks of politics, that is, of leadership.
Given the economic crisis, two convergent phenomena appear to be emerging.
On the one hand, the realization that there is an objective need for authoritative leadership, the request for someone who can handle the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discreditation towards existing leadership, especially economic ones, has proved equally unsuitable and full of dark places.
And together something even deeper and, in a sense, disturbing: discredit, impatience, a sense of incompetence and absence that seeks to dominate the entire ruling class in more and more Western countries.
Indeed, it seems to be spreading more and more among the broad masses of the population of beliefs than that their actions should be the same as the ideas of the still popular elites, as their way of feeling and being, as their culture in the true sense of the word, that the elites have already overcome their time and are indifferent to the opinions of the majority.
The demand for leadership simply nourishes one branch of the subterranean consortium, but a strong movement for the removal of the ruling classes and the traditional political order of the United States manifests itself in the sudden electoral "rebellion" or in the unexpected changes of collective moods in the last and the most recent consortium, from the consortium to the consortium.
