Super glue for walking on the walls
Overcome the laws of gravity thanks to super glue and in the future walk on the walls like Spiderman.
This is the object of various American research centers and now a team of four institutes has come very close to it.
The scientists managed to keep a 100-kilogram body glued to a vertical wall using a sticker of just 2.5 square centimeters.
STUDIUM – The American journal Science has published the findings of some researchers at the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the team of researchers is the development of existing materials that use a special structure of carbon called carbon dwarf tubes.
“The adhesive base can be imagined as a series of tubes laid out like an organized pile of spaghetti,” explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgian Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists were inspired by the legs of the gecko, covered with microscopic hairs that allow the animal to provide the perfect adhesion.
Tests carried out on various materials, such as glass, Teflon and glass paper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the feet of these reptiles and at the same time “simply sticks off the wall,” explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton’s Faculty of Engineering.
"This material could be useful as a temporary adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Perhaps walking on walls like Spiderman? Perhaps yes, but researchers are thinking of far less fascinating uses as a connection of electrical devices, because dwarf carbon tubes are conductors of heat and electricity.
Other applications could relate to aeronautical space engineering .
No superheroes yet.
FURTHER RESEARCH – The University of Berkley, California, is also researching a new adhesive.
In an article in the American Chemical Society magazine, Californian scientists introduced a adhesive formed from microfibers as hair that cleans itself from dust by moving it over the surface to keep it perfectly adhesive.
